function assignTasks(servers, tasks) {
    const result = new Array(tasks.length);
    const freeServers = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < servers.length; i++) {
        freeServers.push([servers[i], i]);
    }
    freeServers.sort((a, b) => a[0] - b[0] || a[1] - b[1]);
    const busyServers = [];

    let time = 0;
    let taskIndex = 0;

    while (taskIndex < tasks.length) {
        while (busyServers.length && busyServers[0][0] <= time) {
            const server = busyServers.shift()[1];
            freeServers.push(server);
            freeServers.sort((a, b) => a[0] - b[0] || a[1] - b[1]);
        }

        while (freeServers.length && taskIndex <= time && taskIndex < tasks.length) {
            const server = freeServers.shift();
            result[taskIndex] = server[1];
            busyServers.push([time + tasks[taskIndex], server]);
            busyServers.sort((a, b) => a[0] - b[0] || a[1][1] - b[1][1]);
            taskIndex++;
        }

        time++;
    }

    return result;
}
```


    The algorithm implemented for each programming languages follows the same logic described below:

1. Create two priority queues called `free_servers` and `busy_servers`. The `free_servers` priority queue will store the free servers following the minimum weight and index order. The `busy_servers` priority queue will store the busy servers following the order of their release time.
2. Add all servers to the `free_servers` priority queue.
3. Iterate through the tasks array using a variable `t` representing the time step.
4. For each time step `t`, check if there is any server in `busy_servers` that became free (i.e., its release time equals the current time step `t`). If there is any, remove it from `busy_servers` and add it back to the `free_servers` queue.
5. If at the current time step `t` there is a task and there is any free server in the `free_servers` queue, assign the task to the smallest free server and add it to the `busy_servers` queue with the updated release time (`t + tasks[i]`, where `i` is the current task index).
6. Continue the loop until all tasks are assigned.

Time complexity: O(n * log(n) + m * log(n)) - At most we are sorting and looping through each server and task in the algorithm.
Space complexity: O(n + m) - We are storing free and busy servers, which have a space complexity proportional to n and the result array which has space complexity proportional to m.

